Democracy Summit Ends, Biden Says Flames of Freedom Never Go Out
The online "Summit for Democracy" ( Summit for Democracy), convened by President Joe Biden and attended by government and civil society and private sector leaders from 110 countries around the world, came to an end Friday (Dec. 10).
In his closing remarks, Biden said the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of every person in the world and can never be extinguished by authoritarian regimes.
He also said he plans to hold a second global "Democracy Summit" next year.
Taiwan's government representative, Councillor Tang Feng, and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Law Kwun-chung, who is currently in exile in the United Kingdom, also spoke at the second day of the summit.
Biden said: "We know how difficult the work ahead of us is.
But we also know that we can rise to the challenge because, as I've said before, as this summit shows, democracy is everywhere in the world.
Authoritarian regimes can never extinguish the tiny flame of freedom that burns in the hearts of people around the world and around the world. "
Biden also said that defending democracy requires the concerted efforts of the entire community.
He said: "As leaders of government, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, to reinforce the parapets of democracy, to push for reform, to achieve transparent and accountable governance, to be more resistant to the buffers and shocks of tyranny, and to those who want to pursue power nakedly before the public good . "
"The second day of the Democracy Summit was devoted to defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
The day coincided with International Human Rights Day.
In his opening remarks, UN Secretary-General Guterres also said that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially from emerging digital technologies.
It is time to reaffirm common values and positions and the resilience of democracy," he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequality, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education, and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires firmly condemning all forms of populism, nativism and extremism, including the use of all the tools offered by the technological revolution. "
In a pre-recorded video address to the summit, Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Lo Kwun Chung reminded participants of the ongoing concern about the human rights situation in Hong Kong and for China's ethnic minorities, including the Uighurs and Tibetans.
For too long, the world has accepted the rise of China without a mechanism to hold it accountable," he said.
That's why politicians and civil society leaders must work together.
We must use all the (resources) we have to ensure that the revival of democracy is our top priority. "
Luo Guancong also called on the free world to unite against the Chinese Communist threat.
Maybe some of you are afraid of upsetting General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, maybe some of you don't recognize the threat [the CCP] poses to our democratic values," he said.
And that's why we're failing.
And that's why we have to change . "
In a roundtable discussion on "Combating Digital Authoritarianism and Affirming Democratic Values," Taiwan Executive Yuan Councilor Tang Feng issued a national statement via video, emphasizing that Taiwan stands at the forefront of the fight against authoritarianism and power.
He also shared his experience on how to fight the new epidemic through information transparency and building mutual trust.
He said, "At a time when democracy in Taiwan is still in its infancy, we have always been at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism and have played a leading role in promoting freedom, democracy and human rights around the world.
During the epidemic, authoritarian governments around the world rationalized human rights abuses in the name of public health and the collective good, and global democracy showed signs of regression.
In Taiwan, however, we don't have to seal off the city to control the epidemic, and we don't have to take it off the shelves to defeat disinformation. "
As the second day of the Democracy Summit got underway, the U.S. Treasury Department announced the imposition of legal sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities in several countries, including China and North Korea, found to have committed serious human rights violations, as well as investment restrictions on a Chinese company found to have used surveillance technology to facilitate human rights abuses.
